256
00:22:39,370 --> 00:22:41,330
- Or even to...
- To optimize it.

257
00:22:41,530 --> 00:22:43,450
Yes, to optimize it.

258
00:22:43,610 --> 00:22:48,410
So that... Yes, you really can say
that. What does it mean for society?

259
00:22:48,570 --> 00:22:52,530
Well-educated women
who are then supposed to be...

260
00:22:52,690 --> 00:22:58,290
After having spent all of 20
years going to school and studying

261
00:22:58,450 --> 00:23:03,810
they're supposed to put all their
effort into raising one or two children?

262
00:23:03,970 --> 00:23:07,610
As far as the state's concerned
that's a huge waste,

263
00:23:07,770 --> 00:23:11,090
from a capitalist standpoint
it is as well.

264
00:23:12,250 --> 00:23:15,890
Basically those women
are supposed to continue

265
00:23:17,010 --> 00:23:21,050
to make their productivity
available to the market.

266
00:23:21,930 --> 00:23:27,010
Nowadays most women have to work. Lots
of women had to do that before too.

267
00:23:27,810 --> 00:23:31,010
But in this day and age
there are more demands.

268
00:23:31,210 --> 00:23:35,290
Women are expected to have
immensely successful careers

269
00:23:35,450 --> 00:23:39,130
while at the same time, and
we haven't yet talked about this,

270
00:23:39,330 --> 00:23:42,570
lofty demands are being put
on mothers and fathers.

271
00:23:42,730 --> 00:23:44,930
You can't just raise
a kid nowadays,

272
00:23:45,090 --> 00:23:48,610
they have to be very gifted
and you have to foster

273
00:23:49,450 --> 00:23:51,650
your children as
much as possible.

274
00:23:52,210 --> 00:23:54,850
I insist upon my
right to laziness.

275
00:23:56,450 --> 00:23:59,730
Like other people insist
upon their right to work.

276
00:24:01,690 --> 00:24:04,730
I've always been
a flop on the job market.

277
00:24:05,770 --> 00:24:07,290
Whatever.

278
00:24:09,530 --> 00:24:12,090
I had a job as a
corpse in the theater.

279
00:24:13,810 --> 00:24:17,050
In this play
that was like three hours long.

280
00:24:18,490 --> 00:24:20,690
I died ten minutes into it.

281
00:24:21,610 --> 00:24:24,210
I lay there, me with
my weak bladder.

282
00:24:25,410 --> 00:24:28,330
I couldn't hold it anymore
after 40 minutes.

283
00:24:29,290 --> 00:24:33,490
And I had to decide if I was going
to pee onstage or go to the toilet.

284
00:24:34,050 --> 00:24:35,810
I chose the toilet.

285
00:24:36,210 --> 00:24:38,570
I got up, went to the toilet,

286
00:24:39,290 --> 00:24:40,770
came back

287
00:24:40,930 --> 00:24:43,090
and lay down in the same place.

288
00:24:45,330 --> 00:24:47,450
No one really noticed.

289
00:24:48,410 --> 00:24:51,530
But the director
totally blew his top.

290
00:24:51,690 --> 00:24:54,930
He was so hot-tempered
he fired me on the spot.

291
00:24:55,690 --> 00:24:59,450
It's absurd, as if anyone
really believed you were dead.

292
00:24:59,610 --> 00:25:01,930
- Yeah!
- That's an idea.

293
00:25:02,090 --> 00:25:04,090
Theater with real corpses.

294
00:25:04,290 --> 00:25:08,010
Maybe with volunteers who want
to live out their final rush.

295
00:25:08,890 --> 00:25:10,810
Yeah, like GG Allin.

296
00:25:12,210 --> 00:25:15,690
He died in front of his audience.
He did it.

297
00:25:17,490 --> 00:25:19,450
Even as a corpse in a theater

298
00:25:20,370 --> 00:25:22,930
you still have no
right to laziness.

299
00:25:44,450 --> 00:25:46,050
Come on.

300
00:25:50,090 --> 00:25:51,850
You coming?

301
00:25:52,610 --> 00:25:54,450
Hey, come on!

302
00:26:01,930 --> 00:26:04,530
That's good. One, two...

303
00:26:04,690 --> 00:26:05,690
three!

304
00:26:07,770 --> 00:26:10,010
Towards me. That's right.

305
00:26:22,730 --> 00:26:24,050
We're nearly done.

306
00:26:37,610 --> 00:26:39,570
Oh yeah, this is...

307
00:26:40,370 --> 00:26:42,770
I don't even know
what his name is.

308
00:26:43,530 --> 00:26:46,810
- Time for a Sexy Lamp Test.
- Oh, you're mean!

309
00:26:48,450 --> 00:26:52,970
We'll take the part out of the script
and replace it with a decorative lamp.

310
00:26:53,130 --> 00:26:56,050
If the story doesn't
change, it's a fail.

311
00:26:56,250 --> 00:26:58,210
Two against one, so...

312
00:27:04,650 --> 00:27:06,650
Man, you guys are so mean!

313
00:27:06,810 --> 00:27:09,850
The guy is really nice,
and a great actor to boot.

314
00:27:10,770 --> 00:27:12,290
- Hello.
- Hello.

315
00:27:12,450 --> 00:27:15,010
Hi. Nice lamp.

316
00:27:16,330 --> 00:27:19,090
- Can we borrow your bike again?
- Yeah.

317
00:27:19,290 --> 00:27:23,810
- Do the Chinese guys still need it?
- The Chinese guys don't need a bike.

318
00:27:24,370 --> 00:27:26,210
Yes, you can take it.

319
00:27:27,450 --> 00:27:31,650
- Have you found a new apartment?
- Mom says we won't with all the dogs.

320
00:27:31,810 --> 00:27:34,730
- What'll you do then?
- Grandma has a yard.

321
00:27:37,530 --> 00:27:40,130
Do we know where
we're going to move yet?

322
00:27:40,330 --> 00:27:43,690
"My husband is my home."
That's what my grandma said.

323
00:27:43,850 --> 00:27:47,810
I mean, what are we doing here
anyway? I mean in the here and now.

324
00:27:48,370 --> 00:27:51,410
Are we different
or are the times different?

325
00:27:51,570 --> 00:27:55,890
We're sitting at a dumb hand-me-down
table with all our old crap.

326
00:27:56,050 --> 00:27:59,250
And all we own is
the cup in our hands.

327
00:28:01,970 --> 00:28:04,810
Wouldn't the situation
be totally different

328
00:28:04,970 --> 00:28:07,610
if we were sitting
in a cozy little garden?

329
00:28:09,890 --> 00:28:12,930
Like in the community
garden Bornholm II?

330
00:28:17,970 --> 00:28:20,770
We're different
people in this situation.

331
00:28:20,970 --> 00:28:24,410
We'd read a Friedrich
Kittler text totally differently.

332
00:28:24,570 --> 00:28:27,410
We may even
interpret it differently,

333
00:28:27,570 --> 00:28:31,050
take the opposing position,
not an affirmative one.

334
00:28:31,250 --> 00:28:35,410
I doubt I'd read it at all. These
brats would have me at my wit's end.

335
00:28:35,810 --> 00:28:38,130
The situation could
be totally different.

336
00:28:38,330 --> 00:28:41,130
Imagine it, we're
sitting in the salon

337
00:28:41,330 --> 00:28:45,530
of a 200-square-meter pre-WWII
apartment on Pariser Strasse.

338
00:28:45,930 --> 00:28:48,930
The nanny
has already put the brats to bed.

339
00:28:49,090 --> 00:28:54,410
Or we didn't have any to begin
with. Right? You not here at all!

340
00:28:59,290 --> 00:29:03,250
Wow! I never thought your
imagination was so bourgeois.

341
00:29:04,090 --> 00:29:08,210
To be honest I find it pretty
strenuous to keep my bearing all day.

342
00:29:08,370 --> 00:29:10,770
I mean, bearing in what sense?

343
00:29:10,930 --> 00:29:14,210
- Towards what?
- I imagine it being quite fun.

344
00:29:15,010 --> 00:29:19,010
You know, when you really get
into it and get a feel for it.

345
00:29:20,370 --> 00:29:23,010
But then it'd be the
only life you have.

346
00:29:25,970 --> 00:29:27,490
Thank you.

347
00:29:36,650 --> 00:29:39,490
We could do
something totally normal.

348
00:29:40,930 --> 00:29:42,450
Yes.

349
00:29:42,850 --> 00:29:46,730
An occupation we never would've
chosen of our own free will.

350
00:30:01,370 --> 00:30:04,530
Right, this is for you.
You can read through it.

351
00:30:06,930 --> 00:30:09,970
Well, if I had to sit here
at my desk every day

352
00:30:10,130 --> 00:30:14,210
I think I'd try to find happiness
in the evenings and on weekends.

353
00:30:14,370 --> 00:30:18,250
- I think that makes lots of things easier.
- I couldn't do it.

354
00:30:19,290 --> 00:30:20,970
But if I had to

355
00:30:21,490 --> 00:30:23,210
maybe then I could.

356
00:30:23,370 --> 00:30:26,250
Maybe you have to have to
to be able to.

357
00:30:26,770 --> 00:30:30,450
And then it makes sense
to rebel against all this crap.

358
00:30:30,970 --> 00:30:35,450
You're right about that, everything
here really is total crap.

359
00:30:35,610 --> 00:30:39,730
We're going on about parallel
worlds. We could do this forever.

360
00:30:39,890 --> 00:30:44,370
Yet it doesn't get us any further
along, and we never go far enough.

361
00:30:44,530 --> 00:30:48,090
A coffee picker in Bali,
a seamstress in Bangladesh,

362
00:30:48,290 --> 00:30:50,850
we jump from one
extreme to the other.

363
00:30:51,890 --> 00:30:55,210
The more extreme we get
the more we neutralize ourselves.

364
00:30:55,370 --> 00:30:56,650
Neutralize?

365
00:30:57,290 --> 00:30:58,610
Yeah.

366
00:30:58,770 --> 00:31:01,370
We always revert
to being ourselves.

367
00:31:03,370 --> 00:31:04,490
Yeah.

368
00:31:04,650 --> 00:31:06,130
Damn!

369
00:31:08,090 --> 00:31:10,890
Yeah, you have
to position yourself.

370
00:31:12,490 --> 00:31:14,410
To find a position.

371
00:31:17,730 --> 00:31:19,650
But within or without?

372
00:31:22,050 --> 00:31:26,530
Do I think from the inside out or
do I see myself from the outside?

373
00:31:29,930 --> 00:31:32,570
I would actually
rather do the latter.

374
00:31:33,250 --> 00:31:35,770
But I fear there is
no "outside" anymore.

375
00:31:35,930 --> 00:31:39,290
The individual has greedily
absorbed that within.

376
00:31:40,330 --> 00:31:42,930
But what you dream
of, or what you mean,

377
00:31:43,090 --> 00:31:45,610
is that everyone is outside.

378
00:31:46,250 --> 00:31:50,290
That no one follows
any rules or any laws anymore.

379
00:31:50,450 --> 00:31:53,530
And that brings us back
to the Red Army Faction.

380
00:31:53,690 --> 00:31:55,290
No, that's baloney.

381
00:31:55,450 --> 00:31:59,650
Even if I were allowed to break laws I
don't know which laws I'd want to break,

382
00:31:59,810 --> 00:32:01,810
let alone demolish.

383
00:32:02,450 --> 00:32:06,490
I can think of one or two things
that one could demolish.

384
00:32:07,610 --> 00:32:09,930
Yes, you as an individualist.

385
00:32:11,770 --> 00:32:13,690
But, in all honesty,

386
00:32:13,850 --> 00:32:15,810
we're all totally sedated

387
00:32:15,970 --> 00:32:18,930
and stupefied
with little gifts and rewards.

388
00:32:21,650 --> 00:32:25,810
And no one voluntarily demolishes
their little reward.

389
00:32:25,970 --> 00:32:27,810
That's a primal instinct.

390
00:32:28,410 --> 00:32:32,330
Sure, but I'm not even that far
along. It's not relevant to me.

391
00:32:32,490 --> 00:32:36,410
Right now I don't have any
possessions that I could defend.

392
00:32:39,330 --> 00:32:43,250
All right then, I'll explain
the entry area to you now.

393
00:32:45,970 --> 00:32:50,250
As you can see it's a prestigious
space, gloriously awash in light.

394
00:32:51,010 --> 00:32:55,330
You could call this room
the centerpiece of the apartment.

395
00:32:55,490 --> 00:33:00,130
Look how the wonderful features of
this old structure are brought to bear.

396
00:33:02,090 --> 00:33:05,690
- Cool, eh?
- That's right, I want to hear a "whoop!"

397
00:33:06,810 --> 00:33:09,650
Yes, now I'll show
you the bathroom units.

398
00:33:10,890 --> 00:33:16,730
You can have them converted and made into
a designer bath and sanitary facilities.

399
00:34:09,690 --> 00:34:11,770
- Hello, Ms. Jaeggi.
- Hello, Nola.

400
00:34:12,410 --> 00:34:15,570
How do you define
the term "forms of life"?

401
00:34:15,970 --> 00:34:19,050
I'll tell you the formula
and then explain it.

402
00:34:19,250 --> 00:34:24,730
They are something akin to inert bundles
or ensembles of social practices.

403
00:34:24,890 --> 00:34:29,290
That alludes to some things that
are key to the term "forms of life."

404
00:34:29,450 --> 00:34:32,090
One is that they
are social practices,

405
00:34:32,290 --> 00:34:37,370
things that people do and that they
do with certain behavioral patterns

406
00:34:37,530 --> 00:34:41,570
that are social in that they are
socially shaped and defined.

407
00:34:42,210 --> 00:34:47,730
When discussing forms of life people
argue about what practices to include.

408
00:34:48,530 --> 00:34:53,210
Is a family still a family if the members
no longer talk or eat dinner together?

409
00:34:53,370 --> 00:34:55,570
- Lots of fighting.
- Interesting.

410
00:34:56,210 --> 00:34:58,890
Is it a city
if it no longer has public places

411
00:34:59,050 --> 00:35:04,410
where people can meet up without
making a date and without paying?

412
00:35:04,570 --> 00:35:07,490
You could say that
contradicts the idea of a city,

413
00:35:07,650 --> 00:35:11,930
or of how we construe the city as a
form of life if such spots are gone.

414
00:35:12,330 --> 00:35:16,050
In the film we dream ourselves
away into other scenarios.

415
00:35:16,250 --> 00:35:21,250
So we're actually a little bit
weary of our existing form of life,

416
00:35:21,410 --> 00:35:23,250
or of existence in general.

417
00:35:23,410 --> 00:35:27,770
So we dream about how it would be
if we had a bourgeois family

418
00:35:27,930 --> 00:35:32,690
or if we had jobs that didn't
allow us so much time to think,

419
00:35:32,850 --> 00:35:35,450
jobs that are a lot
more structured.

420
00:35:36,050 --> 00:35:37,770
But in the end we realize

421
00:35:37,930 --> 00:35:42,970
no matter where we dream ourselves away
to we always revert back to ourselves.

422
00:35:44,330 --> 00:35:46,490
What do you think about that?

423
00:35:46,650 --> 00:35:48,890
I mean, would that change me?

424
00:35:49,050 --> 00:35:52,730
Or, what does a form of life
do with me, as an individual?

425
00:35:52,890 --> 00:35:57,570
The idea that I as an individual am
here and the form or life is here,

426
00:35:57,730 --> 00:36:00,810
like it's some kind of armor
that you slip into,

427
00:36:00,970 --> 00:36:05,970
or as if your form or life were some
kind of a cabin that you walk into

428
00:36:06,130 --> 00:36:09,130
but can also walk back out of
and be yourself.

429
00:36:09,330 --> 00:36:13,090
Yes, that is not
the notion that I...

430
00:36:14,210 --> 00:36:17,290
That isn't the notion
that guides me or that...

431
00:36:18,410 --> 00:36:21,810
I don't assume that,
I basically assume that you...

432
00:36:21,970 --> 00:36:27,210
I assume that getting out of that
socially determined behavioral...

433
00:36:27,370 --> 00:36:31,210
What I mean is that you
can't escape interpretations

434
00:36:31,370 --> 00:36:34,290
of how you see your
life and what you are.

435
00:36:34,450 --> 00:36:37,490
That is, you can't
just step out of them.

436
00:36:38,290 --> 00:36:43,010
When you step out of them you're
still referring back to them.

437
00:36:43,210 --> 00:36:47,330
- A good way to explain that may be...
- There is no neutral space?

438
00:36:47,490 --> 00:36:50,050
- Exactly.
- I'm always in a form of life.

439
00:36:50,250 --> 00:36:53,970
I can't step out into a vacuum
with no form of life

440
00:36:54,130 --> 00:36:55,930
and step into a new one.

441
00:36:56,130 --> 00:37:00,210
But you can still consciously
plan collective forms of life.

442
00:37:00,370 --> 00:37:05,610
Artists living together precariously is
a conscious attempt at a form of life.

443
00:37:05,770 --> 00:37:08,410
One could call
that a form of life

444
00:37:08,570 --> 00:37:11,650
that takes the fluid
or the transitional...

445
00:37:11,810 --> 00:37:15,490
It institutionalizes
the transitional phase.

446
00:37:16,210 --> 00:37:21,250
We were talking about our lack of
bonds, which we actually quite like.

447
00:37:21,410 --> 00:37:26,970
I wanted jump to the way the New Right
interprets what it means to have no bonds.

448
00:37:27,130 --> 00:37:32,490
It sees reviving ties to family and
homeland as the way to save humanity.

449
00:37:33,010 --> 00:37:37,570
So they basically see a lack of
bonds as the plague of humanity.

450
00:37:38,010 --> 00:37:39,650
How do you see that?

451
00:37:39,810 --> 00:37:44,610
Something like that quite crude
notion of homeland and family,

452
00:37:44,770 --> 00:37:48,970
the idea of something you're born
into that is steadfast and undying,

453
00:37:49,130 --> 00:37:54,410
is something that is meant to give us the
guidance we are all allegedly missing.

454
00:37:54,570 --> 00:37:59,330
I think that is a very, very
disastrous interpretation

455
00:37:59,490 --> 00:38:03,690
and a very disastrous diagnosis
that seems to cover a lot of things.

456
00:38:03,850 --> 00:38:07,490
It's why the New Right
call themselves "identitarians."

457
00:38:07,810 --> 00:38:10,090
I think it's important to realize

458
00:38:11,050 --> 00:38:15,610
that a lack of relationships, an
indifference towards the world,

459
00:38:15,770 --> 00:38:18,130
oneself and others
is a real problem.

460
00:38:18,330 --> 00:38:20,770
But that cannot be correlated

461
00:38:20,930 --> 00:38:24,490
to pre-existing,
given and developed

462
00:38:24,970 --> 00:38:27,730
identities and ideas of homeland.

463
00:38:27,890 --> 00:38:31,050
My assumption is
actually the opposite.

464
00:38:31,250 --> 00:38:35,770
I believe that overemphasis, or
that emphasis on what is given,

465
00:38:35,930 --> 00:38:39,770
the emphasis on homeland and
traditional family structures,

466
00:38:39,930 --> 00:38:42,610
is something that
has to do with the fact

467
00:38:43,450 --> 00:38:47,610
that people feel powerless in
the circumstances they live in.

468
00:38:47,770 --> 00:38:50,690
- That they can't shape them...
- Out of fear?

469
00:38:50,850 --> 00:38:52,650
Yes, it's a...

470
00:38:52,810 --> 00:38:56,010
- A realization of impracticability.
- Yes.

471
00:39:05,090 --> 00:39:07,370
That's just how we grew up.

472
00:39:07,530 --> 00:39:11,450
Politics are for politicians
and we, we do something else.

473
00:39:11,610 --> 00:39:14,770
It's established,
like the division of labor.

474
00:39:14,930 --> 00:39:18,090
If we're political at all
then we're the opposition.

475
00:39:18,290 --> 00:39:22,250
That's not really true anymore.
We were the opposition.

476
00:39:22,410 --> 00:39:27,890
Now Pegida, the AfD, right-wingers
and identitarians are the opposition.

477
00:39:28,050 --> 00:39:31,050
So now we're
the opposition to the opposition.

478
00:39:33,010 --> 00:39:34,650
Or we...

479
00:39:35,210 --> 00:39:38,210
Or we work hand-in-hand
with politicians.

