00:39:38,690 --> 00:39:40,370
With the government.

481
00:39:41,770 --> 00:39:43,410
A cabinet of horrors.

482
00:39:43,570 --> 00:39:46,930
But we want to be the opposition,
that's our role.

483
00:39:47,090 --> 00:39:51,650
Oh, guys, opposition aside.
Don't we want to do something?

484
00:39:52,970 --> 00:39:55,730
Make political films
or films in general?

485
00:39:56,730 --> 00:40:01,650
I've seen quite a few political films
that were just political thrillers.

486
00:40:01,810 --> 00:40:05,450
They were about big names
and big-time topics.

487
00:40:07,210 --> 00:40:11,290
I'm definitely going to revolt.
The only question is when?

488
00:40:12,010 --> 00:40:16,690
Whether I'll do it before or
after the Nazis have seized power.

489
00:40:19,450 --> 00:40:23,090
Somehow we have to create
entirely new structures.

490
00:40:23,970 --> 00:40:25,970
To reinvent politics.

491
00:40:26,570 --> 00:40:28,730
Like reinventing the wheel.

492
00:40:30,690 --> 00:40:33,930
We have to start there,
by creating a new -ismus.

493
00:40:34,090 --> 00:40:37,810
- One that doesn't exist yet.
- Yeah, and what should it be?

494
00:40:38,610 --> 00:40:40,490
Empathism, perhaps.

495
00:40:40,930 --> 00:40:43,410
What's that supposed
to be? Rousseau?

496
00:40:43,570 --> 00:40:46,250
Should we start over
from the beginning?

497
00:40:46,410 --> 00:40:49,810
Empathy as a value
anchored in the legal framework.

498
00:40:49,970 --> 00:40:55,290
Not before I've pushed through the right
to earn money with your eyes closed.

499
00:40:56,610 --> 00:41:00,130
Am I the only pragmatic person
in this room or what?

500
00:41:00,730 --> 00:41:05,010
It's not like the refrigerator
fills up overnight on its own.

501
00:41:05,970 --> 00:41:08,970
Well, in a certain
sense it does do that.

502
00:41:09,490 --> 00:41:12,610
Really? How does a
refrigerator fill itself?

503
00:41:13,410 --> 00:41:18,090
Well, Katja managed to crack the lock
to an empty apartment in this building

504
00:41:18,290 --> 00:41:20,930
and to use it as a
nice Airbnb lodging.

505
00:41:21,690 --> 00:41:25,730
- In order to feed the family.
- Let's move beyond the food issue.

506
00:41:26,330 --> 00:41:28,730
We really should
open up our eyes.

507
00:41:30,210 --> 00:41:32,650
Do we really want to see this?

508
00:41:33,930 --> 00:41:37,530
It is high treason
against the German people.

509
00:41:37,690 --> 00:41:41,410
We categorically say no
to expanding immigration

510
00:41:41,570 --> 00:41:44,210
to allow third-country nationals.

511
00:41:44,370 --> 00:41:48,450
It would overstrain our
country's integration capacity.

512
00:41:48,610 --> 00:41:50,130
Lying press!

513
00:41:50,330 --> 00:41:51,810
Lying press!

514
00:41:51,970 --> 00:41:53,570
Lying press!

515
00:41:55,250 --> 00:41:58,210
What does the German oak care

516
00:41:58,570 --> 00:42:01,290
if a warthog rubs against it?

517
00:42:01,690 --> 00:42:05,410
So you'll eventually only get
stale bread and water.

518
00:42:05,570 --> 00:42:08,490
Because that's
what is just for you.

519
00:42:08,770 --> 00:42:10,210
Deport!

520
00:42:10,370 --> 00:42:12,730
Deport! Deport!

521
00:42:27,770 --> 00:42:30,610
- I'm going to make an announcement.
- Yeah?

522
00:42:30,770 --> 00:42:32,770
Listen here, everyone.

523
00:42:33,410 --> 00:42:35,010
Zip them!

524
00:42:36,970 --> 00:42:40,050
As you know this is
our last Wednesday dinner.

525
00:42:40,250 --> 00:42:43,010
We're going to be thrown out
in three days.

526
00:42:43,210 --> 00:42:47,370
Today we sit together, then we
party and then it's over and done.

527
00:42:47,530 --> 00:42:50,890
So I propose that we all
raise our glasses again.

528
00:42:54,690 --> 00:42:57,530
- To a new start.
- Did someone ring?

529
00:43:02,610 --> 00:43:04,250
What's that?

530
00:43:05,250 --> 00:43:07,330
- What is that?
- An ulcer remedy.

531
00:43:07,490 --> 00:43:09,730
Do you have an ulcer
or do you mean us?

532
00:43:12,450 --> 00:43:14,290
Oh, come on.

533
00:43:14,730 --> 00:43:16,650
- Hassan.
- That's a bit mean.

534
00:43:16,850 --> 00:43:19,330
- What's he doing over there?
- Dishes.

535
00:43:19,490 --> 00:43:24,130
- Boy, you guys suck.
- Hey, have a burger to add to your halo.

536
00:43:24,330 --> 00:43:26,050
He's an actor, like we are.

537
00:43:26,250 --> 00:43:30,250
But he fell out with all the
directors and his agency dumped him.

538
00:43:30,410 --> 00:43:33,130
Yeah, and so we
help him with his rent.

539
00:43:33,850 --> 00:43:36,410
He wants to work for it,
so he does dishes.

540
00:43:37,930 --> 00:43:40,850
I saw you on TV
playing a Lebanese drug boss.

541
00:43:41,410 --> 00:43:43,370
Na, dude, don't start.

542
00:43:49,410 --> 00:43:52,530
I'm done with those roles.
Screw stereotypes!

543
00:43:52,690 --> 00:43:54,690
I want to play normal people.

544
00:43:54,850 --> 00:43:58,450
We work, we've been living
here for years. What the hell!

545
00:43:59,970 --> 00:44:05,010
Then play yourself, write your
dialogs. I have a low-budget project.

546
00:44:05,210 --> 00:44:07,930
- What do you say?
- With deferred payment?

547
00:44:08,370 --> 00:44:12,130
- No, I said low-budget, not no-budget.
- Oh, okay.

548
00:44:12,330 --> 00:44:16,010
Dog, don't get me wrong. I have
to do my job. I get a set rate.

549
00:44:16,210 --> 00:44:20,050
- I got you.
- My hourly wage drops the longer we talk.

550
00:44:22,370 --> 00:44:24,850
- Okay.
- That's straight talk.

551
00:44:28,370 --> 00:44:29,970
The art crisis.

552
00:44:32,570 --> 00:44:36,330
The real question is: Does
art always have to be unpaid?

553
00:44:36,490 --> 00:44:41,290
It's more that we differentiate.
We say "no-budget" is art.

554
00:44:41,450 --> 00:44:43,970
If something's
paid it's commercial.

555
00:44:44,130 --> 00:44:48,970
- It's either-or, that causes poverty.
- I make art and my punishment is no money.

556
00:44:49,130 --> 00:44:52,730
For me making loads of dough
doing it would be a disaster.

557
00:44:52,890 --> 00:44:56,410
I don't think he wants that
either, that's why he's here.

558
00:44:56,570 --> 00:45:00,530
So you don't want to be whores,
but what if you love your clients?

559
00:45:00,690 --> 00:45:05,290
If you made really awesome money
doing things that you love?

560
00:45:05,690 --> 00:45:06,890
Paradise.

561
00:45:07,050 --> 00:45:11,770
Yeah, but the market is made up of
people and people desire things.

562
00:45:11,930 --> 00:45:16,010
Do you think people really desire
what they see? Or that it...

563
00:45:16,210 --> 00:45:18,930
- I'd say audiences, the masses...
- Bye.

564
00:45:19,090 --> 00:45:20,610
Bye.

565
00:45:20,770 --> 00:45:22,850
They watch what's shown to them.

566
00:45:23,010 --> 00:45:28,850
The problem we're facing right now is
that critical art is what's in demand.

567
00:45:29,930 --> 00:45:32,490
I don't need money, just burgers.

568
00:46:13,130 --> 00:46:14,810
22/6, first take.

569
00:46:15,250 --> 00:46:16,730
Clapper.

570
00:46:18,090 --> 00:46:19,610
Go ahead.

571
00:46:21,650 --> 00:46:23,610
- Hello, Mr. Hegemann.
- Hello.

572
00:46:23,770 --> 00:46:26,330
Nice to see you.
We are now here...

573
00:46:29,610 --> 00:46:34,490
What if a movie didn't create an
illusion? Would that not be cinema?

574
00:46:35,130 --> 00:46:38,490
When making art in general
and when making political art

575
00:46:38,650 --> 00:46:42,770
you have no choice but to
peek at what's behind the façade.

576
00:46:42,930 --> 00:46:47,850
And no matter how bad it is you
have to concern yourself with it.

577
00:46:48,010 --> 00:46:50,450
That would be a
kind of enlightenment.

578
00:46:50,610 --> 00:46:53,850
But you have to be fully aware
that the audience

579
00:46:54,450 --> 00:46:56,970
always feels it has
been duped then,

580
00:46:57,130 --> 00:47:00,650
because audiences go to
the cinema for that illusion.

581
00:47:00,810 --> 00:47:04,530
But a film that employs
those mechanisms of illusion

582
00:47:04,690 --> 00:47:09,370
to present a successful revolution
or a strong socially critical plot

583
00:47:09,530 --> 00:47:14,010
without breaking the illusion is
perhaps not all that political.

584
00:47:14,210 --> 00:47:17,730
- According to Brecht...
- Then it's more manipulative?

585
00:47:17,890 --> 00:47:19,410
Yes.

586
00:47:20,130 --> 00:47:22,130
It's probably without effect.

587
00:47:22,330 --> 00:47:27,290
You watch it, are moved and maybe
you shed a tear and that's that.

588
00:47:27,450 --> 00:47:31,290
Brecht said people
are lulled into the illusion

589
00:47:31,450 --> 00:47:34,290
and no longer construe
the world as alterable.

590
00:47:34,450 --> 00:47:39,530
You can only construe it is as alterable
when you free yourself from the illusion.

591
00:47:40,330 --> 00:47:45,130
That doesn't exist anywhere else,
it only exists on this stage.

592
00:47:45,330 --> 00:47:50,890
That a grown person can claim they
are the King of Denmark or similar.

593
00:47:51,770 --> 00:47:53,770
And that is interesting,

594
00:47:53,930 --> 00:47:58,570
because if you were to do that in
real life, if you were to dress up...

595
00:47:59,290 --> 00:48:02,290
That great suit you're wearing
is borderline.

596
00:48:02,450 --> 00:48:04,530
- It's almost a costume.
- Yeah.

597
00:48:04,690 --> 00:48:09,090
- If you walk around in that...
- I get stared at walking around the city.

598
00:48:09,690 --> 00:48:11,730
As Hamlet I'd probably be...

599
00:48:11,890 --> 00:48:15,050
If I said I was Hamlet
I'd be put in a psychiatric ward.

600
00:48:15,250 --> 00:48:18,650
Or if you were to put on a tie
and stick a moustache on

601
00:48:18,810 --> 00:48:20,610
and claim to be a man.

602
00:48:21,130 --> 00:48:25,090
Wearing a glued on moustache in
the theater is no problem at all.

603
00:48:25,290 --> 00:48:29,730
People believe it, people accept
that kind of mixing of identities.

604
00:48:29,890 --> 00:48:35,250
But mixing up life with a theater
stage, that can be really dangerous.

605
00:48:35,730 --> 00:48:40,250
It is simply extremely liberating
when you can say what you think.

606
00:48:40,410 --> 00:48:43,210
A colleague
who is your age recently told me

607
00:48:43,370 --> 00:48:46,610
she didn't know anyone
among her acquaintances

608
00:48:46,770 --> 00:48:49,090
who still says what they think.

609
00:48:49,490 --> 00:48:51,930
People can't afford
to do that anymore.

610
00:48:52,090 --> 00:48:55,570
But what kind of a society,
what kind of life is it

611
00:48:55,730 --> 00:48:59,330
when you only ever say what's
suitable in a given moment

612
00:48:59,490 --> 00:49:01,690
and the other
person does that too?

613
00:49:01,850 --> 00:49:04,450
Then you live in a
totally illusory world,

614
00:49:04,610 --> 00:49:09,850
then the theater of social roles
is truly detached from the people.

615
00:49:10,010 --> 00:49:14,330
- And that's why it's so liberating and...
- Then we're all zombies.

616
00:49:14,490 --> 00:49:18,850
We can say that this stage is
exemplary because people here,

617
00:49:19,010 --> 00:49:24,210
where others stay objective and cool
when they try to lodge a tiny objection,

618
00:49:24,370 --> 00:49:27,770
people here yell, that's
why there's so much yelling.

619
00:49:27,930 --> 00:49:33,770
That's because here people can use their
voice to express authentic thoughts.

620
00:49:33,930 --> 00:49:39,370
And that truth and seriousness, you
really can't act as if it were so.

621
00:49:39,530 --> 00:49:43,930
It seems you can only do that onstage,
where it's not forbidden to yell.

622
00:49:44,090 --> 00:49:46,730
In my script it says
we ride Bobby Cars now.

623
00:49:46,890 --> 00:49:48,730
If it say so, we have to do it.

624
00:49:48,890 --> 00:49:51,890
I doubt it's conducive
to self-optimization.

625
00:50:05,970 --> 00:50:10,610
- This is chic too.
- I think it makes you look old somehow.

626
00:50:11,210 --> 00:50:13,450
- The fur, not you.
- Um-hm.

627
00:50:14,650 --> 00:50:17,410
Yeah. Or maybe
a two-piece outfit...

628
00:50:17,570 --> 00:50:19,570
"This rapidly changing city

629
00:50:19,730 --> 00:50:24,050
"that made its flaw of a lack of
tradition into a sign of modernity."

630
00:50:25,290 --> 00:50:27,730
That sounds like it
could be from now.

631
00:50:27,890 --> 00:50:30,650
But it was written
by Robert Walser in 1908.

632
00:50:31,210 --> 00:50:33,690
"Makeshift
existence suits Berlin,

633
00:50:33,850 --> 00:50:38,050
"where people are eager for anything
new, quickly pass over yesterday

634
00:50:38,250 --> 00:50:40,410
"and nothing stays as it was."

635
00:50:43,690 --> 00:50:45,690
That's still true today too.

636
00:50:53,010 --> 00:50:57,930
"To Robert Walser Berlin is a body,
a dream populated by Berlin's women.

637
00:50:58,730 --> 00:51:02,210
"He wants them all, the
naive, voluptuous violent lady

638
00:51:02,370 --> 00:51:05,490
"and the good little girl
from Kurfürstendamm."

639
00:51:06,130 --> 00:51:08,010
- Button it up, right?
- Yeah.

640
00:51:08,210 --> 00:51:10,330
"Berlin is a giant lady.

641
00:51:21,770 --> 00:51:26,210
"Contemporaries continually stress
the analogy of Berlin and its women

642
00:51:26,370 --> 00:51:28,890
"Robert Musil, Carl Zuckmayer...

643
00:51:30,010 --> 00:51:31,650
"These quotes have

644
00:51:31,810 --> 00:51:35,530
"a striking mix of incredulous
adulation, erotic attraction

645
00:51:35,690 --> 00:51:40,410
"and restrained aggression that they
use to describe the city and its women."

646
00:51:40,570 --> 00:51:42,450
This is still the 1920s.

647
00:51:46,090 --> 00:51:48,410
"The spry and firm big-city girls

648
00:51:48,570 --> 00:51:51,610
"with their insatiable
open mouths grow annoyed

649
00:51:51,770 --> 00:51:55,130
"when my eyes settle too long
on their gliding shoulders

650
00:51:55,330 --> 00:51:57,210
"and floating cheeks."

651
00:52:00,130 --> 00:52:02,370
A certain Franz Hessel.

652
00:52:15,410 --> 00:52:17,570
More "Berlin as woman."

653
00:52:17,930 --> 00:52:19,370
"The 'rubble woman.'

654
00:52:19,690 --> 00:52:23,890
"Youthful beauty contrasts
with the rubble she sorts.

655
00:52:24,450 --> 00:52:29,770
"In the mid-1980s Helmut Newton shot
his 'boardinghouse photos' in Berlin."

656
00:52:30,210 --> 00:52:33,010
That sounds good.
"Fräulein Petra."

657
00:52:59,490 --> 00:53:01,850
"Ten years later, Jürgen Teller.

658
00:53:02,490 --> 00:53:07,050
"Cloudy puddles, rusty iron doors,
barred windows, dismal trees,

659
00:53:07,250 --> 00:53:09,410
"garbage, construction cranes.

660
00:53:09,930 --> 00:53:13,570
"Teller's Berlin photos
look like a hastily opened gift

661
00:53:13,730 --> 00:53:16,930
"whose contents disappointed
and were cast aside.

662
00:53:17,090 --> 00:53:21,210
"He photographs flawed female
bodies that don't fit any ideal:

663
00:53:22,050 --> 00:53:27,050
"thighs adorned with red spots,
lips ripped open, elbows too raw."

664
00:53:29,290 --> 00:53:30,890
Heroin chic?

665
00:53:31,410 --> 00:53:32,890
Me again.

666
00:53:41,650 --> 00:53:46,610
"He reacts to the dematerialization
of existence with vulnerable bodies

667
00:53:46,770 --> 00:53:48,610
"that tell stories.

668
00:53:48,770 --> 00:53:53,410
"In Berlin he seeks phenomena that
open themselves up to narratives.

669
00:53:55,210 --> 00:53:58,650
"The girl in the sweater
with Hölderlin in her pocket,

670
00:53:58,810 --> 00:54:01,490
"as Harold Nicholsen
described in 1929,

671
00:54:01,650 --> 00:54:04,330
"had become a junkie after 1961."

672
00:54:05,570 --> 00:54:09,410
I'm the girl in the sweater. I
have Hölderlin in my pocket too.

673
00:54:23,130 --> 00:54:25,450
The City and Its Bodies.

674
00:54:26,330 --> 00:54:28,250
The City of Women.

675
00:54:29,730 --> 00:54:31,770
No, that was another film.

676
00:54:34,890 --> 00:54:38,130
And behind that façade
lurks an immense void.

677
00:55:09,490 --> 00:55:11,850
- Hello, Ms. Allmendinger.
- Hello, Nola.

678
00:55:12,010 --> 00:55:16,010
I interviewed students for my
film and what stood out to me

679
00:55:16,210 --> 00:55:20,650
was most of them answered the questions
in relation to their own futures

680
00:55:20,810 --> 00:55:24,090
but never in the context
of society as a whole.

681
00:55:24,290 --> 00:55:28,290
And I was wondering if it was
due to my questioning technique

682
00:55:28,450 --> 00:55:31,930
that it always went in
that individualistic direction.

683
00:55:32,090 --> 00:55:35,330
People naturally start
talking about themselves.

684
00:55:35,490 --> 00:55:39,010
We know that, and so we
have to resort to measures

685
00:55:39,210 --> 00:55:43,370
to make them move on to talking
about society of their own accord,

686
00:55:43,530 --> 00:55:48,970
or to get them to extrapolate from
themselves to their social circle

687
00:55:49,130 --> 00:55:52,410
or to what they think
about society and the world.

688
00:55:52,930 --> 00:55:57,210
So you can of course do that by
sitting in a bar for a long time

689
00:55:57,370 --> 00:55:59,090
drinking beer with them

690
00:55:59,290 --> 00:56:03,290
and you'll get that in what
we call a "narrative interview."

691
00:56:03,450 --> 00:56:07,570
But you don't get anything
representative with that.

692
00:56:07,970 --> 00:56:10,850
We start with just what
you were criticizing.

693
00:56:11,010 --> 00:56:13,770
We want people
focused on themselves,

694
00:56:13,930 --> 00:56:16,130
so they notice how they feel.

695
00:56:16,730 --> 00:56:19,610
And that they begin
with themselves alone.

696
00:56:19,770 --> 00:56:23,570
And we do that
by trying to shut down cognition.

697
00:56:23,730 --> 00:56:25,530
They shouldn't think.

698
00:56:25,690 --> 00:56:29,890
And then we give them these
surfaces. This is a kind of mat.

699
00:56:30,050 --> 00:56:34,090
This is rough, this is glass,
this is corrugated cardboard.

700
00:56:34,290 --> 00:56:38,010
- And we say...
- And it works. You immediately...

701
00:56:38,210 --> 00:56:42,210
- You feel...
- We ask, "How does your life feel today?

702
00:56:42,370 --> 00:56:45,210
- "Just tell me how life feels today."
- Yeah.

703
00:56:45,370 --> 00:56:49,810
What the media tells them, what they
read in books is immediately gone.

704
00:56:49,970 --> 00:56:52,570
Think about how your life feels.

705
00:56:53,050 --> 00:56:56,610
You can do it differently.
I can have you smell this.

706
00:56:57,210 --> 00:57:00,010
How does your
life smell? Like this?

707
00:57:00,210 --> 00:57:02,330
Or does life smell like this?

708
00:57:03,570 --> 00:57:07,610
And voilà! You forget what
people have been telling you.

709
00:57:07,770 --> 00:57:10,730
We don't want that.
We can read that in the paper.

710
00:57:10,890 --> 00:57:13,130
We're interested in your opinion.

711
00:57:13,330 --> 00:57:17,250
When we have them at a point
where they've attained inner peace

712
00:57:17,410 --> 00:57:20,490
and have forgotten all else,
then we get started.

713
00:57:20,650 --> 00:57:24,690
Then we ask, "How important is
a feeling of togetherness to you?

714
00:57:24,850 --> 00:57:27,210
"How important is that to you?"

