783
01:04:50,410 --> 01:04:52,930
- Nice to see you.
- I'm glad you're here.

784
01:04:53,090 --> 01:04:56,290
We've chosen
this very futuristic location.

785
01:04:56,450 --> 01:04:59,210
Do you feel
like you're in the future here?

786
01:04:59,930 --> 01:05:03,810
Yes, perhaps, inasmuch
as this place reminds me of

787
01:05:04,690 --> 01:05:08,130
how I imagined the future
when I was a child.

788
01:05:09,250 --> 01:05:11,970
When I read books and saw movies

789
01:05:12,370 --> 01:05:14,730
this is more or less
how I imagined it.

790
01:05:14,890 --> 01:05:17,330
It seems to me that for a period,

791
01:05:17,490 --> 01:05:20,850
in the 19th century,
at the start of the 20th century

792
01:05:21,010 --> 01:05:23,490
and into the 1960s and 1970s,

793
01:05:23,650 --> 01:05:26,690
people still thought
a lot about the future.

794
01:05:26,850 --> 01:05:31,530
And people had the feeling
that they could shape the future.

795
01:05:32,130 --> 01:05:37,850
That you could push a project through,
develop a vision, so to speak,

796
01:05:38,010 --> 01:05:39,730
and then realize it.

797
01:05:39,890 --> 01:05:44,250
There was this idea
of a sort of human omnipotence.

798
01:05:44,730 --> 01:05:46,490
But now, more and more,

799
01:05:46,810 --> 01:05:49,850
the future is becoming
an event to us.

800
01:05:50,370 --> 01:05:51,930
An event

801
01:05:52,370 --> 01:05:54,210
that's new to us.

802
01:05:54,570 --> 01:05:56,690
We're not really prepared.

803
01:05:56,850 --> 01:06:00,530
It often comes as
something unexpected.

804
01:06:01,690 --> 01:06:05,450
And we have the feeling
that we should constantly adapt.

805
01:06:05,930 --> 01:06:09,050
I believe that our
strategic behavior

806
01:06:09,250 --> 01:06:13,530
has increasingly become a strategy
of adapting to the future.

807
01:06:14,490 --> 01:06:17,650
I sometimes call
that "self-updating."

808
01:06:17,810 --> 01:06:20,330
In one of your texts

809
01:06:21,330 --> 01:06:23,130
you talk about film and say

810
01:06:23,330 --> 01:06:27,970
film contains a paradox between
vita contemplativa and vita activa.

811
01:06:28,130 --> 01:06:31,090
That screen heroes
are hyperactive.

812
01:06:31,330 --> 01:06:33,770
They shoot, they jump,

813
01:06:34,330 --> 01:06:36,570
they have to achieve heroic aims,

814
01:06:36,730 --> 01:06:40,290
and the viewer
automatically becomes passive

815
01:06:40,450 --> 01:06:44,450
because he or she sits statically
in a chair in a theater seat.

816
01:06:45,770 --> 01:06:50,610
How can you become capable of
acting in the face of that paradox?

817
01:06:50,770 --> 01:06:54,330
Or how can you induce
the viewer to become active?

818
01:06:54,490 --> 01:06:57,090
By getting the viewer

819
01:06:57,290 --> 01:07:02,650
to internally identify with
the movie's heroic character.

820
01:07:03,490 --> 01:07:06,850
What you described
as internal movement of thought?

821
01:07:07,010 --> 01:07:08,970
- Not movement of thought.
- No?

822
01:07:09,130 --> 01:07:10,330
No.

823
01:07:10,490 --> 01:07:13,290
Neither the hero can think...

824
01:07:13,890 --> 01:07:16,690
- The hero can't think?
- He can't think.

825
01:07:17,290 --> 01:07:20,930
The hero has to act heroically.

826
01:07:21,850 --> 01:07:25,050
And when you act heroically
you don't think.

827
01:07:25,930 --> 01:07:28,930
And the viewer
isn't supposed to think either.

828
01:07:29,090 --> 01:07:32,490
The thinking viewer
was a big mistake of Brecht's.

829
01:07:32,650 --> 01:07:34,850
The viewer should identify...

830
01:07:35,010 --> 01:07:38,250
The viewer should
identify with the movie.

831
01:07:38,410 --> 01:07:41,810
The viewer should
identify with the hero.

832
01:07:42,570 --> 01:07:45,930
And if that hero
is a revolutionary

833
01:07:47,250 --> 01:07:52,090
the viewer will try to adopt the
same position, the same attitude.

834
01:07:52,850 --> 01:07:56,530
But via identification,
Brecht was anti-identification.

835
01:07:56,690 --> 01:07:59,250
Yes, but I'd say
via identification.

836
01:07:59,410 --> 01:08:00,890
Ultimately...

837
01:08:02,530 --> 01:08:04,610
you have to...

838
01:08:05,570 --> 01:08:07,610
You become revolutionary

839
01:08:07,770 --> 01:08:12,410
when you feel like you're
in a movie in real life.

840
01:08:13,370 --> 01:08:16,130
- Yeah?
- That's the premise. You have to...

841
01:08:16,330 --> 01:08:18,850
- Like you're in a movie in real life?
- Yes.

842
01:08:19,010 --> 01:08:20,690
Or like you're in a novel.

843
01:08:20,850 --> 01:08:24,930
The true revolutionary is
romantic. What does that mean?

844
01:08:25,090 --> 01:08:27,570
It means life is
like a novel to him.

845
01:08:27,930 --> 01:08:30,410
If, just for a moment,

846
01:08:31,050 --> 01:08:34,970
he crashed back down
into reality, so to speak,

847
01:08:35,610 --> 01:08:39,010
then the revolution
and the romanticism is over.

848
01:08:39,970 --> 01:08:44,090
That means that only
as long as I live in that...

849
01:08:45,010 --> 01:08:49,530
Only as long as I live in
that totally artificial reality,

850
01:08:50,930 --> 01:08:53,970
which is more real
to me than any reality,

851
01:08:54,570 --> 01:08:57,210
am I capable of
inciting a revolution.

852
01:08:57,370 --> 01:09:00,330
The moment that reality becomes

853
01:09:00,730 --> 01:09:03,410
a kind of quotidian misery...

854
01:09:04,130 --> 01:09:06,930
When I perceive reality
as quotidian misery

855
01:09:07,090 --> 01:09:12,250
